    "comment": "Rationale: This paper uses measurements of synaptic Ca2+ (Figure 3F) and release probability (4C) in wild-type and calretinin knock out mice. This shows elevated synaptic Ca2+ and increased transmitter release consistent with its role as an endogenous fixed buffer.\n\n24/01/2018 Pim\n- A kinetic model is fitted that postulates Calretinin as a fast calcium buffer. The model is validated in Calretinin KO mice. Calretinin has 6 Ca2+-binding domains (EF hands).. Experimental description: Materials and Methods: Patch-clamp recordings were performed at 20°C-22°C on acute slices prepared from 21- to 27-day-old C57BL/6 or CR-/- mice...........................",
